ons of people like President Yeltsin's adviser, Colonel-General Dmitri Volkogonov, and the German historian Professor Klaus-Jurgen Muller, comes a book which for the first time challenges the official Soviet historiography and offers the first truly global picture of the war in Russia.From Nazi-Soviet relations at the start of the war, and the Soviet Union's response to the German attack, Barbarossa moves to the little examined subject of the invasion's aftermath. And offering dramatic new evidence on Hitler's objectives, Stalin's strategy and readiness for war, the Battle of Moscow, and Japan's wartime policy towards the Soviet Union, this book also deals with the previously taboo subjects of the personalities and politics of collaboration and the massive human toll of the invasion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh1 aBiber, Dusan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDilks, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDilks, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorodetsky, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinsley, H. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffreys-Jones, Rhodri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKudryashov, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMertsalov, Andrei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMikoyan, Stepan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Klaus-Jü